text: Dietary carotenoids and Vitamin A are thought to be important factors in the development of ﬂounder
label: BODY

text: pigmentation.  However, supplementation of these compounds has yielded mixed results (Kanazawa, 1993,
label: BODY

text: Takeuchi et al., 1995).  Retinoic acid (RA) is a hormone derived from carotinoids and Vitamin A.  RA has
label: BODY

text: been used to stimulate pigmentation development in the Japanese ﬂounder, Paralichthys olivaceus (Miwa
label: BODY

text: and Yamano, 1999, Haga et al., 2002).  This study examined the effect of RA on pigmentation development
label: BODY

text: in summer ﬂounder, Paralichthys dentatus.  Larvae were immersed in 5 and 10 nM concentrations of RA
label: BODY

text: for a period of 10 days preceding metamorphosis.  Fish were reared for an additional 20 days following
label: BODY

text: treatment.  Nearly all ﬁsh in the study developed normal ocular side pigmentation.  Fish in the control
label: BODY

text: group also expressed normal development on the blind side.  However, over 60% of the ﬁsh in the treatment
label: BODY

text: groups expressed partial or total pigmentation of the blind side.   These results support a role for retinoic
label: BODY

text: acid in the pigmentation development of ﬂounder.

text: Hogchokers (Trinectes maculates) are one of the dominant ﬁshes in Delaware Bay based on a
label: BODY

text: seven-year (1996-2002) survey of intertidal and subtidal creeks. In order to learn more about their basic
label: BODY

text: life history, specimens were collected during May to November from 1999-2002 to determine spatial and
label: BODY

text: temporal patterns of reproduction. Seven marsh creek systems representing lower (12-18 ppt), middle
label: BODY

text: (5-7 ppt) and upper (0-5 ppt) bay along the New Jersey side of Delaware Bay were sampled monthly
label: BODY

text: with replicate tows of a 4.9-meter otter trawl (6-mm cod end mesh). Initial observations based on length
label: BODY

text: frequency distributions and spatial/temporal patterns show potentially mature individuals (85-140-mm TL)
label: BODY

text: frequenting the lower bay during spawning season where salinity is highest. Intermediate sizes (60-85 mm
label: BODY

text: TL) were found further upstream while abundance of young-of-year (YOY) (35-60 mm TL) peaks were
label: BODY

text: found where salinity is the lowest. The differentiation of size classes along a salinity gradient is consistent
label: BODY

text: with the Dovel (1969) model. Veriﬁcation by calculating a monthly Gonadosomatic Index (GSI) over three
label: BODY

text: years helps deﬁne the reproductive pattern of hogchokers in response to seasonal shifts of environmental
label: BODY

text: factors such as temperature and salinity.

text: Comparisons of species richness estimates reveal interesting patterns regarding the ecological
label: BODY

text: biogeography of ﬂatﬁshes.  Within all regions, ﬂatﬁshes are most diverse where extensive continental shelves
label: BODY

text: with complex habitats are located in shallow water.  Generally, diversity of marine ﬂatﬁshes increases along
label: BODY

text: continental shelves from polar to equatorial waters, with maximum diversity of ﬂatﬁsh assemblages usually
label: BODY

text: occurring on tropical and subtropical continental shelves within each ocean.  Flatﬁsh diversity is also high
label: BODY

text: at continental shelf areas where components from different faunal provinces intermix.  Lower than expected
label: BODY

text: diversity is noted on continental shelf regions where cold-water currents and upwelling occur.  In all oceans,
label: BODY

text: but especially in the West Paciﬁc, ﬂatﬁsh diversity is lower at insular compared with continental locations
label: BODY

text: This interdisciplinary study evaluated spatiotemporal patterns of abundance, geographic variation in
label: BODY

text: growth and maturity, larval transport, morphometry, and genetics of the yellowtail ﬂounder in the northeastern
label: BODY

text: United States. The results suggest that yellowtail ﬂounder found on the principal U.S. ﬁshing grounds
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: southwest Georges Bank to Nantucket. Geographic patterns of size and proportion mature at age indicate
label: BODY

text: two “phenotypic stocks” of yellowtail ﬂounder, with a boundary along the northern edge of Georges Bank
label: BODY

text: to Nantucket.  Therefore, yellowtail from the southern New England ﬁshing grounds form a separate
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: U.S. areas.  Genetic analysis also found little variation among U.S. samples.  U.S. yellowtail ﬂounder
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: As part of a program to assess the feasibility of winter ﬂounder, Pseudopleuronectes americanus,
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: To determine optimal release size, the predator-prey size relationship between winter ﬂounder and
label: BODY

text: the green crab, Carcinus maenas, was examined. The number of ﬂounder killed per day was signiﬁcantly
label: BODY

text: higher (31%) in winter ﬂounder < 20-mm compared to all other larger ﬁsh size classes (4-8% killed/day).
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: and of colors matching their own pigment.
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: In the aquaculture of summer ﬂounder (Paralichthys dentatus), the inherent variation in growth
label: BODY

text: and settling behavior during metamorphosis may lead to cannibalism and necessitate increased labor due
label: BODY

text: to size grading. Our goal was to use an environmental salinity change to synchronize settling behavior
label: BODY

text: and produce a uniformly sized cohort of juvenile summer ﬂounder. Early metamorphic summer ﬂounder
label: BODY

text: (Age: 41 dah) were exposed to either a 5-day ﬂuctuating (30-20-30-20-30 ppt; “Flux”) or a single (30-20
label: BODY

text: ppt; “Low Salinity”) drop in rearing salinity. The Flux group was reared at 30 ppt while the Low Salinity
label: BODY

text: group remained at 20 ppt until sampling at 61 dah. A control (continuous 30 ppt) was used for comparison.
label: BODY

text: For all treatments, the initial n=60 ﬁsh/tank, and 3 tanks/treatment. Settling behavior in the control was
label: BODY

text: prolonged, with the Peak Settlement Interval (PSI; deﬁned as the interval beginning on the day the ﬁrst
label: BODY

text: 20% settled until the day 80% had settled) requiring 8 days. Settling behavior was synchronized by the
label: BODY

text: Low Salinity treatment, with the PSI reduced to 5 days. The Flux treatment negatively affected settling
label: BODY

text: behavior with the PSI increased to 10 days. By 61 dah, average ﬁsh size was increased by the Low Salinity
label: BODY

text: treatment (19.3 ± 0.5 mm), but not the Flux treatment (17.2 ± 0.4 mm), compared to the control (17.6 ± 0.5
label: BODY

text: mm). Developmental stage at 61 dah was signiﬁcantly increased in the Low Salinity treatment (3.2 ± 0.1)
label: BODY

text: in comparison to the Flux (2.9 ± 0.1), but not the control (3.1 ± 0.1). However, the Low Salinity treatment
label: BODY

text: reduced variance in development. To conﬁrm the positive effects of the Low Salinity treatment, a second
label: BODY

text: experiment was performed. A single salinity drop (30-20 ppt) at 37 dah (Low Salinity2) was compared to
label: BODY

text: a control (continuous 30 ppt). In this experiment, the Low Salinity2 treatment did not synchronize settling.
label: BODY

text: The PSI for the Low Salinity2 treatment was 14 days while the control was 13 days. Additionally, by 58
label: BODY

text: dah, average ﬁsh length (16.8 ± 0.2 mm) and developmental stage (2.9 ± 0.1) in the Low Salinity2 treatment
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: the control. Percent survival was unaffected by treatment in both experiments. In aquaculture, the effective
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: Marine teleosts are hypoosmotic to their surrounding environment and must continuously drink
label: BODY

text: seawater to avoid dehydration.  It is widely accepted that water uptake across the marine teleost intestine
label: BODY

text: is driven by active absorption of monovalent ions (Na+ and Cl-).  However, intestinal transport of divalent
label: BODY

text: ions (SO42-, Mg2+, and Ca2+) has been less intensively studied.  In this study, SO42- transport by winter
label: BODY

text: ﬂounder (Pseuodopleuronectes americanus) intestine was characterized in Ussing chambers.  Under short-
label: BODY

text: circuited conditions and 1 mM SO42- on both sides, net active SO42- secretion (blood-to-lumen) occurred
label: BODY

text: (7.42 ± 0.63 nmoles x cm-2 x hr-1).  Treatment with NaCN (10 mM) or ouabain (0.1 mM) inhibited net
label: BODY

text: secretion indicating dependence on metabolism and the plasma membrane Na+ gradient.  Luminal treatment
label: BODY

text: with the anion exchange inhibitor 4, 4’-diisothiocyanatostilbene-2-2’-disulfonic acid (DIDS, 0.2 mM) also
label: BODY

text: inhibited net secretion.  Removal of Cl- alone, and Cl- and HCO3- together from the luminal bath solution
label: BODY

text: reduced net SO42- secretion.  Removal of HCO3- alone stimulated net secretion.  Sulfate uptake into foregut
label: BODY

text: brush-border membrane vesicles was stimulated by a trans-Cl- gradient (in>out), and unaffected by a trans-
label: BODY

text: HCO3- gradient (in>out).  Short-circuiting with K+, in=out, and valinomycin had no effect on Cl--stimulated
label: BODY

text: SO42- uptake suggesting electroneutral exchange.  These data indicate that the winter ﬂounder intestine
label: BODY

text: actively secretes SO42- by exchanging for luminal Cl-.  This process may function in water absorption and
label: BODY

text: in the maintenance of plasma SO42- homeostasis.

text: The Georges Bank ﬁsh community has undergone drastic changes over the past several decades,
label: BODY

text: including dramatic declines in the abundance of key ﬂatﬁsh species.  Many of these declines have been
label: BODY

text: attributed to intensive ﬁshing pressure.  Flatﬁsh are both directly susceptible to ﬁshing gears and indirectly
label: BODY

text: susceptible to the impact of those gears on the ocean bottom. Thus, Georges Bank ﬂatﬁshes play multiple
label: BODY

text: roles as populations highlight the need to understand the role of these ﬁsh as predators, competitors, and prey.
label: BODY

text: We present estimates of relative abundance for major ﬂatﬁshes from research surveys, which demonstrate
label: BODY

text: that even with a recent recovering trend for a few species due to area closures, most ﬂatﬁshes are far from
label: BODY

text: their levels of historical abundance.  Because ﬂatﬁshes serve as a major energy pathway for conversion of
label: BODY

text: benthic production into a form suitable for consumption by higher predators and humans, we then examined
label: BODY

text: the diet of nine major ﬂatﬁshes from this ecosystem including primarily polychaete- crustacean feeding
label: BODY

text: or piscivorous species, with one echinoderm specialist.  From this information, we assess the magnitude
label: BODY

text: of predation by ﬂatﬁsh on other components of the food web.  Additionally, we evaluate the degree of
label: BODY

text: competition among the ﬂatﬁshes and between the ﬂatﬁshes and other ﬁsh species via diet overlap, spatial
label: BODY

text: overlap, interaction coefﬁcient estimates, and cross-correlation of population abundances.  Skates are the
label: BODY

text: primary competitor of ﬂatﬁshes in this ecosystem and have the potential to competitively depress some
label: BODY

text: ﬂatﬁsh populations.  Finally, we explore the implications of ﬂatﬁsh trophic ecology with respect to different
label: BODY

text: ﬂatﬁsh population recoveries and how the Georges Bank ecosystem may function in the future.

text: Winter ﬂounder abundances have experienced dramatic declines throughout the greater Narragansett
label: BODY

text: Bay estuarine system, including within Mt. Hope Bay and the Sakonnet River.  In Mt. Hope Bay in
label: BODY

text: particular, the decline of winter founder has been suggested to be more severe than in other regions and
label: BODY

text: is often attributed to the impact of the Bryton Point Power Plant.  The major reason for this assertion is
label: BODY

text: that the decline in Mt. Hope Bay was coincident with a large increase in the power plants cooling water
label: BODY

text: intake and efﬂuent in 1984.  We have examined time trends in the abundance of winter ﬂounder and other
label: BODY

text: species from 11 different areas within the Narragansett Bay system based on trawl data collected by the
label: BODY

text: Rhode Island Department of Environmental Protection from 1979-2001.  Most areas exhibit decline
label: BODY

text: patterns similar to that of Mt. Hope Bay.  Mt. Hope Bay declines are not signiﬁcantly greater than other
label: BODY

text: comparable areas, and in fact are less than declines in Greenwich Bay and the Sakonnet River. A further
label: BODY

text: examination of the spatial-temporal patterns in the greater Narragansett Bay reveal that shallow semi-
label: BODY

text: enclosed areas have exhibited the greatest declines and that declines are stronger for juvenile size classes
label: BODY

text: than for adults.  These patterns suggest an overall shrinkage of winter ﬂounder’s distribution in the bay.
label: BODY

text: We also examined spatial temporal patterns in the ﬁsh assemblage and ﬁnd that the Narragansett Bay ﬁsh
label: BODY

text: community has undergone a dramatic shift from benthic to pelagic species.  This pattern is strongest in
label: BODY

text: the shallow embayments (Greenwich Bay, Sakonnet River, Mt. Hope Bay, Wickford Harbor and upper
label: BODY

text: Narragansett Bay), and weakest in the deep central bay and adjacent Rhode Island Sound areas.  These
label: BODY

text: patterns are consistent with community structure changes associated with eutrophication.  We suggest that
label: BODY

text: changes in the abundance of winter ﬂounder and ﬁsh species assemblages in Mt. Hope Bay and greater
label: BODY

text: Narragansett Bay over the last 25 years is symptomatic of widespread eutrophication.

text: Predator-prey dynamics between the sand shrimp, Crangon septemspinosa, and juvenile winter
label: BODY

text: ﬂounder were examined in laboratory experiments to assess the joint effects of varying prey density and
label: BODY

text: temperature on shrimp foraging behavior and mortality of ﬂounder. The functional response of shrimp to
label: BODY

text: six densities of ﬂounder was determined at two temperatures (10 and 16 °C).  Moreover, the behavioral
label: BODY

text: mechanisms underlying the shrimp’s functional response (encounters, attacks, captures, and handling time)
label: BODY

text: were quantiﬁed with visual observations and compared to the foraging parameters predicted by continuous-
label: BODY

text: time functional response models.  Shrimp consumption rates increased signiﬁcantly with increasing ﬂounder
label: BODY

text: density, irrespective of water temperature.  At low ﬂounder densities, however, signiﬁcantly more ﬂounder
label: BODY

text: were consumed at 16 °C then at 10 °C.  Analysis of proportional mortality of ﬂounder across prey density
label: BODY

text: revealed a positively density-dependent (sigmoidal) type-III functional response at 10 °C, and an inversely
label: BODY

text: density-dependent (hyperbolic) type-II functional response at 16 °C.  Based on model parameter estimates
label: BODY

text: and visual observations of predator foraging behavior, differences in functional responses were attributed
label: BODY

text: to increased shrimp activity (and encounters) at higher ﬂounder densities and temperature.  These ﬁndings
label: BODY

text: indicate that shrimp are capable of driving young-of-the-year ﬂounder populations to local extinction
label: BODY

text: during warm water conditions.

text: A plausible regulatory mechanism, based on predation of early life history stages of the winter
label: BODY

text: ﬂounder, Pseudopleuronectes americanus, was developed utilizing a reproduction curve with three
label: BODY

text: equilibrium points.  This type of reproduction curve was ﬁrst suggested by Walters (1986), but apparently
label: BODY

text: has not been tested with empirical data to date.  We ﬁtted a ﬁve-parameter curve to the relationship between
label: BODY

text: spawning stock size and recruitment to Age 1 which contained three equilibria and which explained more
label: BODY

text: than 80 percent of the variability in the data from the Niantic River, Connecticut.  This type of relation can
label: BODY

text: arise when a predator follows a sigmoid functional response in their consumption rates of early life history
label: BODY

text: stages (larvae).  If the predator population remains ﬁxed over time, the prey stock may display a stable
label: BODY

text: equilibrium at two stock sizes (S1 and Sh).  The stock size between these two stock sizes (Su) is an unstable
label: BODY

text: level from which the stock will collapse to a lower value or grow towards the high equilibrium value
label: BODY

text: (Sh).  Following the initial work of Taylor (this conference), the sand shrimp, Crangon septemspinosus, is
label: BODY

text: implicated as a major predator of winter ﬂounder at early life history stages.  Using a segmented regression
label: BODY

text: technique, we demonstrate that there is some coherence between the decline of the winter ﬂounder stocks
label: BODY

text: and the relative abundance of predators.  We conclude that this work suggests that the predator pit region
label: BODY

text: of the reproduction curve may account for the delayed recovery of southern New England winter ﬂounder
label: BODY

text: stocks.

text: Throughout history, statutory laws have been enacted that unexpectedly create conﬂicts between
label: BODY

text: government agency objectives. Over the last half-century, the conﬂicts between mandates that favor
label: BODY

text: water resource development and environmental protection of those same waters have become evermore
label: BODY

text: contentious.  The focusing of legal intent to the point where they can occur, now, within a single agency
label: BODY

text: has facilitated these mission conﬂicts.  The passage of supplemental legislation in furtherance of either
label: BODY

text: mandate has narrowed the focus and sharpened the conﬂict with the result that agencies are compelled to act
label: BODY

text: against each other.  The conﬂicts between the three resource agencies (US Fish & Wildlife Service [FWS],
label: BODY

text: the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration / National Marine Fisheries Service [NMFS], the
label: BODY

text: US Environmental Protection Agency [EPA]) and the US Army Corps of Engineers (Corps) are legendary.
label: BODY

text: Today, as we move into the twenty-ﬁrst century, the conﬂict between improving Port infrastructure by
label: BODY

text: providing adequate access and the need to protect public trust resources living within the same waters
label: BODY

text: has become a national concern.  The conﬂict is embodied in time-of-year restrictions on dredging and
label: BODY

text: disposal of sediment.  Resolution of the matter is problematic because the objectives cannot be reconciled
label: BODY

text: in mutual mandates or economic frameworks.  For example, invocation of a seasonal window to protect
label: BODY

text: aquatic resources may preclude a single, continuous dredging of a desired access channel.  Valuation of the
label: BODY

text: dredging and cost delays is possible, but valuing aquatic resource impacts is not an equally well-grounded
label: BODY

text: practice.
label: BODY

text: Because winter ﬂounder are unique in their spawning and early life stage characteristics, they tend
label: BODY

text: to engender agency conﬂict and special note in EFH Conservation Recommendations. Through a series
label: BODY

text: of serendipitous and focused investigations NMFS has come to be the source of much of the controversy.
label: BODY

text: Species sensitivity, spawning concentration identiﬁcation, and early life stage movements are the issues
label: BODY

text: that have come to be the basis for negotiating resource protective objectives under the EFH program.
label: BODY

text: Local knowledge of these matters is vital as are the advances made in dredging and our understanding of
label: BODY

text: the impacts associated with it.  Much of this interplay has taken place in the waters off the New England
label: BODY

text: coastline.  Today, NMFS routinely invokes seasonal constraints on any activities that might diminish winter
label: BODY

text: ﬂounder EFH from January to June.

text: Flatﬁshes, such as the summer ﬂounder (Paralichthys dentatus), provide unique opportunities to study

text: the development of morphological asymmetry. We have examined left/right differences in squamation and
label: BODY

text: pigmentation throughout early development in P. dentatus, documenting scale development and location in
label: BODY

text: relation to age, size, and overall pigmentation pattern (normal, albino, or ambicolored).  General patterns
label: BODY

text: of scale development in P. dentatus resemble those in Japanese ﬂounder (P. olivaceus; Seikai, 1980).  In
label: BODY

text: both species, scale development progresses from posterior to anterior, and from the center of each side out
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: Research into the culture of the California halibut, Paralichthys californicus, is comparatively new
label: BODY

text: but has the advantage of building on information gathered for other ﬂatﬁsh aquaculture candidates. This
label: BODY

text: presentation compares what information is available for the California halibut to that for other ﬂatﬁsh
label: BODY

text: species.  As with other ﬂatﬁsh, a combination of rotifers followed by enriched brine shrimp nauplii and
label: BODY

text: some formulated feed were initially used for rearing California halibut larvae.  The employment of a static
label: BODY

text: green-water type system in the second season of research dramatically increased the numbers of larvae
label: BODY

text: brought through metamorphosis.   Substantial improvements in weaning were also made during the second
label: BODY

text: year of the project in which weaning was achieved as early as 42 days, compared to over 100 days in the
label: BODY

text: ﬁrst year.
label: BODY

text: The characteristic morphology and behavior of metamorphosed ﬂatﬁsh offer a number of advantages
label: BODY

text: to culturists.  All the ﬂatﬁsh being considered for culture are temperate species but increases in growth rate
label: BODY

text: are noted with limited increases in temperature.  A summary of growth rates (Speciﬁc growth rate; SGR,
label: BODY

text: %/day) for a number of ﬂatﬁsh species with notes on culture conditions and feed is presented.  Work to
label: BODY

text: date with the various ﬂatﬁsh species suggests, as with other marine species, a high requirement for dietary
label: BODY

text: protein.  Although lipid requirements have yet to be deﬁned it is thought they will most easily be satisﬁed
label: BODY

text: through the use of marine lipids.  Conversely, meeting these requirements for protein and marine lipids
label: BODY

text: undoubtedly will be expensive.  Fortunately, in that these ﬁsh spend much of their time lying motionless
label: BODY

text: on the bottom, food conversion should be particularly attractive.  In addition, provision of inputs such as
label: BODY

text: oxygen and removal of wastes should be less of a challenge that for actively swimming species. It appears
label: BODY

text: that culture density of ﬂatﬁsh, as deﬁned by coverage of the tank bottom, can be surprisingly high.  Some
label: BODY

text: species have been grown at densities over 100%, which necessitates the ﬁsh stack on top of each other.
label: BODY

text: One other particularly interesting component of ﬂatﬁsh culture is the potential for various ﬂatﬁsh to be
label: BODY

text: cultured in an environment of reduced salinity.  This could allow culturists to move away from expensive
label: BODY

text: coastal sites.  Information available with regard to growth and survival of various ﬂatﬁsh species under
label: BODY

text: reduced salinity conditions is summarized.  While we are still in the process of researching many of the
label: BODY

text: above culture components, work to date suggests that the California halibut has the potential to become
label: BODY

text: one of a number of ﬂatﬁsh species that will be commercially cultured in the future.

text: Our prior research indicated that coves near Little Egg Inlet, New Jersey are settlement areas for
label: BODY

text: winter ﬂounder (Pseudopleuronectes americanus), and that estuarine circulation patterns in this ﬂood-
label: BODY

text: dominated system supported the advection of larvae into these coves.  The purpose of the present study
label: BODY

text: was to determine the vertical distribution of larvae.  We performed both surface and bottom plankton tows
label: BODY

text: (bongo nets) synchronously with repeated Acoustic Doppler Current Proﬁler (ADCP) transects over the
label: BODY

text: study area. Despite tidal currents approaching 2 m/s, our observations indicate that the temporal variability
label: BODY

text: of larval abundances cannot be explained solely on horizontal advection. On average, more larvae (42-
label: BODY

text: 489.8/1000m3) were collected at the bottom than at the surface (0-233.0/1000m3). We always collected
label: BODY

text: larvae at the bottom, but collected no larvae at the surface 31% of the time. These results, in conjunction
label: BODY

text: with results from simultaneous 1-m plankton tows, indicate the importance of behavior in the advection
label: BODY

text: of these larvae into settlement coves. Larvae that migrate to the bottom of the channel during the ebb may
label: BODY

text: avoid being swept out the inlet and instead may move to the surface during the subsequent ﬂood to ﬁnd
label: BODY

text: suitable settlement habitat within the estuary.

text: The Marine Recreational Fisheries Statistics Survey (MRFSS) program of the National Marine
label: BODY

text: Fisheries Service (NMFS) is a national program designed to estimate marine recreational ﬁnﬁsh total
label: BODY

text: catch, and angler effort and participation.  It consists of a voluntary intercept survey of ﬁshermen upon
label: BODY

text: completion of their ﬁshing trip and provides information on species catch and associated lengths and
label: BODY

text: weights.  The purpose of the present study is to demonstrate the value of the MRFSS program in providing
label: BODY

text: important data to ﬁsheries biologists despite the relatively small number of ﬁshes collected.  Between 1997
label: BODY

text: and 2001, the combined catch of the summer ﬂounder, Paralichthys dentatus, and the southern ﬂounder,
label: BODY

text: Paralichthys lethostigma, contributed up to 8% of the recreational total catch in North Carolina, 8.1% in
label: BODY

text: South Carolina, 2.9% in Georgia, and 4% in eastern Florida.  However, North Carolina was the only state
label: BODY

text: in which summer ﬂounder dominated the ﬂounder catch.  The contribution of ﬂounder ranged from a low of
label: BODY

text: 1.3% (GA, 1997) to a high of 8.1% (SC, 2000). In 1998, a 12-inch size restriction was placed on ﬂounder
label: BODY

text: and we investigated the impact of this regulation.  Using only data provided by DNR in Georgia for southern
label: BODY

text: ﬂounder, there was a signiﬁcant difference in the ﬁsh sizes collected over the years.  In 1997, 42% of the
label: BODY

text: ﬁsh were under 12 inches, but only 10% were undersized in 2001.  This encouraging news indicates that
label: BODY

text: recreational ﬁsherman seem to follow guidelines regarding size restrictions.

text: Young of the year winter ﬂounder (Pseudopleuronectes americanus) from Sandy Hook Bay suffered
label: BODY

text: unexpectedly high mortality (45% in seven days) when held on sediments from a shallow area (0.5 m MLW)
label: BODY

text: of Newark Bay off Bayonne NJ.  Fish were randomly allocated to tanks containing either clean sand or
label: BODY

text: Newark Bay sediment for the purpose of generating treatment and control animals to competitive predation
label: BODY

text: experiments.  Tanks were well ﬂushed resulting in a maximum dissolved oxygen concentration gradient
label: BODY

text: of less than 6 μM (0.2 mg/L) from inlet to outlet.  Mortality was minimal among controls on clean sand,
label: BODY

text: but in the tank containing Newark Bay sediment some ﬁsh were found dead on top of sediment and many
label: BODY

text: more had died while buried, suggesting the latter had not made an effort to escape the lethal conditions.
label: BODY

text: The shallow depth (3 cm) of sediment employed and the measures taken to preclude hypoxia in the water
label: BODY

text: suggest that constituents of Newark Bay sediment other than biogeochemicals were responsible for the
label: BODY

text: mortality.

text: Hogchokers (Trinectes maculatus) are an abundant component of estuarine systems in the mid-
label: BODY

text: Atlantic Bight.  Despite their abundance, little is known about hogchoker biology and their trophic role
label: BODY

text: in general.  This study was undertaken to provide new information on aspects of abundance, movement,
label: BODY

text: growth, and reproduction of hogchokers in the Hudson River estuary.  Hogchokers were collected during
label: BODY

text: monthly bottom trawl surveys of the Lower Hudson River estuary during the spring through autumn of
label: BODY

text: 2002.  Fish were collected during 5-minute tows of two otter trawl sets at each of 10 stations spanning from
label: BODY

text: lower Manhattan (Battery) to Newburgh, New York.  Abundances and location of captured young-of-the-
label: BODY

text: year, older juveniles and adults were recorded.  These ﬁsh were processed at the laboratory for body length
label: BODY

text: and weight, gender, and liver and gonad weights.  The liver and gonadal weights were used to compute
label: BODY

text: hepatic-somatic and gonadal-somatic indices, respectively, in order to identify spawning time and to deﬁne
label: BODY

text: the role that the liver might play in ﬁsh condition and reproductive effort.  Results of this study will be
label: BODY

text: compared with earlier results from the Hudson River and Delaware Bay.

label: BODY

text: Blackcheek tongueﬁsh, S. plagiusa, are abundant in shallow coastal waters and have insigniﬁcant
label: BODY

text: value as a sport ﬁsh or for the commercial ﬁshing industry.  In order to assess the behavioral patterns of one of
label: BODY

text: the least understood ﬂatﬁshes, observations were performed over a 48-h period in a controlled environment.
label: BODY

text: Individuals were caught via trawl, measured, and randomly placed in separate experimental chambers (84
label: BODY

text: x 43 x 34 cm) within 36 h of capture.  Chambers contained 1 cm of clean graded sand and 10 cm of water
label: BODY

text: (30oC and 29 ppt at start of experiment).  To determine if any diel or tidal rhythmicity existed, ﬁsh were
label: BODY

text: observed in approximate 3-h intervals in correspondence with high, ebb, low, and ﬂood tide.  A light with
label: BODY

text: a red ﬁlter was used at night to minimize disturbance.  Diel activity was quantiﬁed by noting the percent
label: BODY

text: of the tongueﬁsh body covered by sediment.  That, in conjunction with data regarding whether individuals
label: BODY

text: changed orientation or changed location, was utilized to determine activity patterns.  Preliminary results
label: BODY

text: suggest that blackcheek tongueﬁsh were more active at night as indicated by less sediment coverage and
label: BODY

text: the fact that ﬁsh changed location frequently.  Future studies will focus on whether interaction between
label: BODY

text: tidal stage and light level affects tongueﬁsh movement patterns.

text: Summer ﬂounder, Paralychthys dentatus, ranks among the top ﬁnﬁsh landed in both Virginia’s
label: BODY

text: commercial and recreational ﬁsheries. Under the Summer Flounder Fishery Management Plan, incremental
label: BODY

text: increases of recreational ﬁshery minimum size limits in 2002 to 394 mm TL (VA’s coastal ﬁshery) and 444
label: BODY

text: mm TL (VA’s Chesapeake Bay ﬁshery), coupled with angler bag limits and 1-2 week mid-summer ﬁshery
label: BODY

text: closures, are contributing to rebuilding of the stock. Requiring anglers to release greater proportions of their
label: BODY

text: catches also provided an opportunity to learn more about the distribution and habitat use patterns of 1-3 year
label: BODY

text: old ﬂounder through the Virginia Game Fish Tagging Program (VGFTP). Beginning in 2000 the VGFTP has
label: BODY

text: tagged over 10,800 juvenile ﬂounder (through July 2002; ﬁsh typically 279-381 mm TL). Approximately
label: BODY

text: 900 recaptures have been reported (8 % return rate). Fish are tagged in the caudal peduncle musculature
label: BODY

text: with a Hallprint T-bar tag (anchor-10-mm long; sheath 65-mm long), a tag having approximately100%
label: BODY

text: retention and producing no signiﬁcant tagging mortality (from 3-10 day cage trials with tagged ﬁsh).
label: BODY

text: Most tagging, and subsequent recaptures, occurred at ﬁshing piers, bridge-tunnel complexes, and jetties.
label: BODY

text: At several locations in 2001, 7-15 multiple recaptures (2-5 recaptures of the same tagged ﬁsh) provided
label: BODY

text: unique data showing that some ﬁsh remained in the vicinity of certain structure sites over signiﬁcant periods
label: BODY

text: of time, i.e., May through July/August and September-November. For example, a ﬁsh was recaptured on
label: BODY

text: three separate occasions at the same pier between June and August (serial periods at large of 32/44/and 67
label: BODY

text: days); similarly, a ﬁsh recaptured ﬁve times at the same pier demonstrated site ﬁdelity over serial periods
label: BODY

text: of 12/13/50/58/and 74 days. At another pier a tagged ﬁsh was recaptured three times at the site during
label: BODY

text: September-November (serial periods of 2/19/and 64 days). Recaptures of ﬁsh tagged during one year and
label: BODY

text: recaptured the next year also demonstrate some occurrences of year-to-year site ﬁdelity, both for sites in
label: BODY

text: lower Chesapeake Bay as well as sites around ocean inlets. Short and long distance movements of ﬂounder
label: BODY

text: have also been demonstrated. Recaptures of ﬂounder tagged at the Chesapeake Bay mouth have occurred
label: BODY

text: from off Cape May (NJ), Long Island Sound (NY), North Carolina, and South Carolina beaches, a general
label: BODY

text: pattern observed in earlier VIMS studies (1987-89 and 1995-96).

text: Summer ﬂounder, Paralichthys dentatus, is an increasingly important aquaculture species in the
label: BODY

text: U.S.  Like most other marine ﬁshes, however, its early development is poorly known, mainly due to the
label: BODY

text: historical difﬁculty of obtaining pelagic embryonic and larval stages. The cooperation of a commercial
label: BODY

text: hatchery has enabled us to prepare a detailed staging table for embryonic and larval development using large
label: BODY

text: numbers of embryos of known ages reared under controlled conditions.  Our staging scheme is designed
label: BODY

text: to facilitate rapid assessment of developmental stage based on readily visible landmark features, while
label: BODY

text: providing more detailed descriptions of the morphological differentiation of the jaw apparatus and digestive
label: BODY

text: system. We divide development into two main periods, pre-hatching and post-hatching, each of which is
label: BODY

text: further subdivided into discrete morphological stages.  Pre-hatching stages (fertilization to hatching) are
label: BODY

text: based loosely on Shardo’s (1995) staging table for Alosa sapidissima; post-hatching stages (hatching to
label: BODY

text: metamorphosis) are aligned with the staging table for Japanese ﬂounder (Paralichthys olivaceus; Minami,
label: BODY

text: 1982; Fukuhara, 1986).  The appearance and increasing complexity of discrete morphological features
label: BODY

text: provides a more reliable and less variable measure of development than do simple scalar measures such as
label: BODY

text: length, width or age.  This staging scheme should therefore facilitate accurate assessments of developmental
label: BODY

text: stage, which are important both for a wide range of applied studies (for example on larval nutrition), and
label: BODY

text: for basic descriptive and experimental research in this species.
label: BODY

text: Seasonal changes in blood chemistry and hematology were observed in yellowtail ﬂounder, Limanda
label: BODY

text: ferruginea, collected from the Northwest Atlantic. Variations in blood parameters appear to be regulated
label: BODY

text: by seasonally-induced physiological and/or environmental factors. Plama osmolalities during the winter,
label: BODY

text: spring and summer seasons were signiﬁcantly greater than in the fall. Sodium concentrations peaked during
label: BODY

text: the winter and declined during spring and fall. Potassium was highest in the summer and lowest during
label: BODY

text: the winter. Calcium was signiﬁcantly higher in fall than spring. Hematocrit was highest in the spring and
label: BODY

text: lowest during the fall. Hemoglobin values were elevated during the winter and spring months and declined
label: BODY

text: during the fall. This baseline collection of blood data may be useful in monitoring the health and condition
label: BODY

text: of yellowtail ﬂounder in nature or under aquaculture conditions.

label: BODY

text: The decline of traditional ground ﬁsheries gives urgency to aiding the crisis by augmenting
label: BODY

text: indigenous populations with hatchery-reared ﬁsh. Winter ﬂounder (Pleuronectes americanus) may be an
label: BODY

text: excellent candidate for stock enhancement.  From 1997 to the present, Llennoco, Inc. has been successfully
label: BODY

text: spawning adult winter ﬂounder, growing out juveniles and tagging winter ﬂounder for stock enhancement.
label: BODY

text: From 2000 to the present, Marine Research, Inc. has successfully transported, released and recaptured those
label: BODY

text: hatchery-reared ﬁsh.  Issues have been addressed and obstacles overcome in the process, particularly in the
label: BODY

text: areas of maintaining broodstock, life support systems, food supply and distribution, monitoring systems,
label: BODY

text: transportation methods, tagging, release and recapture.  The hatchery methods utilized by Llennoco, Inc.
label: BODY

text: have proven that it is economically and biologically feasible to produce millions of juvenile winter ﬂounder
label: BODY

text: at a reasonable cost.  The procedures developed by Marine Research, Inc. have shown that the hatchery-
label: BODY

text: reared winter ﬂounder do survive following release in Plymouth and Duxbury Harbors.  Recaptured
label: BODY

text: individuals obtained by beach seine as much as 95 days post-release showed good growth rates and cage
label: BODY

text: studies suggested that survival rates may be equal between tagged hatchery-reared ﬁsh and naturally
label: BODY

text: occurring ﬁsh.  Stomach content analyses showed that the diets of released hatchery-reared ﬁsh and wild
label: BODY

text: ﬁsh were identical.  As a result of these efforts, it appears that winter ﬂounder may be used for large-scale
label: BODY

text: enhancement program.

text: As part of a previous study in 1994, 24 gravid female winter ﬂounder were ﬁtted with acoustic
label: BODY

text: transmitters and released in New Haven Harbor, CT prior to the spawning season. The transmitters sent out
label: BODY

text: a unique numerical signal so that individual ﬁsh could be identiﬁed. We visited the harbor weekly during
label: BODY

text: spawning season and systematically searched the harbor for tagged ﬁsh using a directional hydrophone.
label: BODY

text: Areas where ﬁsh were found were thought to be potential spawning areas.  Fish were frequently located
label: BODY

text: in Morris Cove on the eastern side of the harbor and around the east breakwater. Using a benthic sled, we
label: BODY

text: then sampled these areas in an effort to collect fertilized winter ﬂounder eggs and to conﬁrm the presence
label: BODY

text: of spawning activity at the site.
label: BODY

text: Since only a few winter ﬂounder eggs were collected in 1994, the same six sampling sites were
label: BODY

text: sampled more intensively in 1997.  Triplicate tows were conducted at each site approximately biweekly from
label: BODY

text: February to the beginning of April.  In 1999, four sites in the shallower areas of Morris Cove were sampled
label: BODY

text: using the same protocol as for the six sites sampled in 1997. In total, over 1400 eggs were collected, 115 of
label: BODY

text: which were winter ﬂounder eggs.  The greatest number of winter ﬂounder eggs was collected in mid-March
label: BODY

text: in both years. The observed distribution of winter ﬂounder eggs indicates that the northern end of Morris
label: BODY

text: Cove and the area adjacent to it and east of the main channel are spawning areas for winter ﬂounder.

text: Atlantic halibut, Hippoglossus hippoglossus, is currently being explored as an aquaculture candidate
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: feed conversion ratio (FCR). Juvenile ﬁsh (20g; 20/tank) were reared at 13ºC in 140 l tanks in a closed
label: BODY

text: recirculating system (n=three replicates/treatment) over an 84-day period. The ﬁsh were fed one, three
label: BODY

text: and ﬁves times daily over a 12-hour period under constant lighting. A signiﬁcant difference in growth was
label: BODY

text: observed between ﬁsh fed one and ﬁve times daily (p< 0.05). Fish fed once daily consumed signiﬁcantly less
label: BODY

text: feed during this study (731.7g) than those fed three or ﬁve times daily (856.3g and 888.7g, respectively).

text: There was no signiﬁcant difference in feed conversion ratio (FCR) among treatment groups.

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: group), entrained to one feeding per day, was monitored by video for 72-h periods.  Video recordings of
label: BODY

text: ﬁsh movement were digitized and converted to histograms for statistical analysis. Preliminary analysis did
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: We have applied two complementary techniques to document skin and pigmentation development
label: BODY

text: in summer ﬂounder: parafﬁn histology, which shows both general skin structure and the speciﬁc location
label: BODY

text: of melanophores, and a biochemical (DOPA) assay that reveals melanophores at early stages of their
label: BODY

text: differentiation.  In newly-hatched larvae (stage A; Martinez and Bolker, 2002), the skin is not yet divided
label: BODY

text: into distinct dermal and epidermal layers; this morphological distinction begins to appear at stage C, and
label: BODY

text: is well developed by the onset of metamorphosis (stage F).  No early melanophores are detectable by the
label: BODY

text: DOPA assay at stage A, but scattered cells on both ocular and blind sides show a positive DOPA reaction
label: BODY

text: by stage E (late premetamorphosis); this pattern continues through stage H (late metamorphosis).  No
label: BODY

text: DOPA-reactive cells are detectable at later stages.  In metamorphosed larvae 50 days after hatching, a layer
label: BODY

text: of melanin is present between the dermal and epidermal layers of ocular-side skin, but absent on the blind
label: BODY

text: side.  Scales and scale pockets, which extend deeply into the dermis, begin to develop by 75 days after
label: BODY

text: hatching; melanin is localized mainly at the base of the epidermis on the ocular side.  In juveniles (>60
label: BODY

text: mm), dermal melanophores gradually replace epidermal melanin as the primary basis of dark pigmentation
label: BODY

text: on the ocular side, though some extracellular melanin remains in the epidermis.  Malpigmented juveniles
label: BODY

text: display the same skin structure and melanin distribution as normal individuals at the histological level;
label: BODY

text: however, albino ﬁsh show typical blind-side morphology in ocular-side skin, and ambicolored ﬁsh have
label: BODY

text: ocular-type skin and pigmentation on both sides of the body.

label: BODY
